file cmnds
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
scp - secure copy
scp <localfile> <remoreuser>@<remotemachine>:<remotepath> - local to remote copy
scp <remoteuser>@<remotemachine>:<remotepath> - remote to local cophy

wget - dobwload file from server to computer
wget <filedownload path url>

process managemnt
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
ps/top - to get running process
ps -aux  - it will give snapshot, to get list refresh itself by top cmnd

kill - to kill the running task, ps id will get ps cmnd; kill <pid>

service - manager servercies
service --status-all   to print list of services
service <service_name> status - to print detaus status of a service
sudo service <servicename> restart/stop - to restart/stop service


mount &unmont
-------------------------------------------------------
lsblk/fdisk - to list block devices n manipulate dispartitions
sudo mount <partitontomount> <localmountignpoint> - sudo mount dev/sda2  /mnt
sudo unmount <localmountingpoint>

filter
--------------------------------
grep - aloows to search specific char/string...; ls -l | grep ".*.py$" - to filer only py files

run prog in bacground - program &
------------------------------------------

write to n read from files
------------------------------------------
ls -l | grep ".*py$" > filename.txt
cat filename
grep "word" < filename


run multiple cmnds at a time - separate with ;
--------------------------------------
and conditons a||b, a&&b - regular expression

head&tail
-------------------------
-n -  lines
-c - byetes
-q - quiet - print files content without mentioning file name when multiple files printed
-v - verbose - print file names along with content
-f - log entries written by running prgs

/etc - config files
swtching users - sudo username
wc - word count
wc -l : Prints the number of lines in a file.
wc -w : prints the number of words in a file.
wc -c : Displays the count of bytes in a file.
wc -m : prints the count of characters from a file.
wc -L : prints only the length of the longest line in a file.

basic and general commands
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
~$ pwd-to know the current dir
ls-list of files in current dir, for hidden files ls -a
cd -
cd <dir>(*casesensitive),
for white space in filename abc xyz - cd <abc/xyz>
for go to home dir cd
for go back to folder cd..
mkdir - to create dir, for whiter space use /
rmdir - to delete empty dir, for delete dire containing files rm
rm -r - to just delete dir
touch - to create file touch <filename.format>
man & -help  - shows how to use and more about command,
man cd shows manual pages of cmnd; cd -help shows how to use it
cp - copy; cp <file.format> <path>
mv - move r rename; mv <filename> <filename>
locate - to search file; -i to ignore casesensitive; locate -i <filename>; if whitespace use *
echo - to keep data to file; echo sampledatatext.....abc>>filename
cat - to view the data in the file; cat filename
nano,vj,jed - text ediotrs with colors
sudo - super user do; needed "sudo passwd" cmnd for to set root pswd
sudo bash/ su - to enter into root cmnd line (it displays path from root)
df - for disk space, for megabytes -m; df -m; for file usage df filename
du - dis usage of folder du foldername
ls -lah - to files sizes in folder
tar - compress/uncompress tar archieves;
for creating .tar archive - tar -cvf
for untar - tar -xvf
for list contents  - tar -tvf
zip & unzip - zip archieves
uname -a - to print the system details like kernla,version,date release, process typee
apt-get - to work with packages install/update/upgrade required root previliges
sudo apt-get install package
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get upgrade
sudo apt-get dist-upgrade; distro
apt-cache search - to search pkg
chmod - to make file executable and to change permissions; sudo chmod +x filename
chmod +rwx
chmod -rwx
chmod +x filename to allow executable permissions.
chmod -wx filename to take out write and executable permissions.
hostname - hostname -I; i for ipadress
ping - to check connection to a server; ping google.com
clear  - clear ternimal
cntl+c - stop cmnd in terminal safely
cntl+z - force stop
exit - exit terminal
sudo halt & sudo reboot - poweroff and reboot
TAB - to fill the terminal; cd doc > TAB >
